<subSubSection pageId="41" pageNumber="100" type="remarks">
<paragraph pageId="41" pageNumber="100">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="41" pageNumber="100">
This is a widespread species that is distributed from western Europe to the Far East, including North Africa and the Near East (
<bibRefCitation author="Danilevsky, ML" journalOrPublisher="International almanac" pageId="48" pageNumber="107" url="http://cerambycidae.net/catalog.pdf" year="2018 a">Danilevsky 2018a</bibRefCitation>
). The larvae develop under the bark of deciduous trees, but they usually choose the poplar 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Salicaceae" genus="Populus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Populus" order="Malpighiales" pageId="41" pageNumber="100" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">Populus</taxonomicName>
and the willow 
<taxonomicName class="Ascidiacea" family="Polycitoridae" genus="Salix" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Salix" order="Aplousobranchia" pageId="41" pageNumber="100" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Salix</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Danilevskaya, GB" journalOrPublisher="Entomologische Zeitschrift" pageId="47" pageNumber="106" pagination="171 - 178" title="Cerambycidae collected in North-East Kazakhstan by an international collecting trip 2005 (Coleoptera)." volume="119" year="2009">Danilevskaya et al. 2009</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="41" pageNumber="100">Numerous specimens were collected on the bark of harvested poplars, while some of them were attracted to artificial light sources (Fig. 15H).</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
